  "text": "Immediately after explantation and preparation of the hearts, an equilibration interval of 15 min was allowed to establish steady-state conditions. Baseline measurements of coronary effluent and transudate were performed in the last 2 min before induction of 20 min of warm (378C), global stopped-flow ischaemia. Samples of effluent were collected again throughout min 0-5, 5-10, 10-15, and 15-20 after the onset of reperfusion. Transudate samples were collected over 2 min intervals at 0-2, 2-4, 4-6, 6-8, 12-14, and 18-20 min after the start of reperfusion. Therefore, during the first-decisive-minutes of perfusion, all fluids coming from the heart were collected and quantified gravimetrically. Since the rate of transudate formation is pressure-dependent, [CITATION_1] we related it to the respective perfusion pressure established at the given flow rates in each heart.",
